\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES exactness theorem and $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions (iter-026)}

After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequenceIso} the comparison iso is in place. Iter-026 closes the LES proper with three short one-liners on top of the iter-023 sequence iso, mirroring Mathlib \texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L140--149 line-by-line for the $\ModuleCat\,k$ flavor: the exactness theorem $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ plus the two $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions $\HModulePrime\_\delta\_\toBiprod$ and $\HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\_\delta$.

\begin{lemma}[Mayer-Vietoris LES exactness theorem (iter-026)]
  \label{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_sequence_exact}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence,def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequenceIso,lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_shortComplex_shortExact}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category, $J$ a Grothendieck topology on $C$, $S : J.\mathtt{MayerVietorisSquare}$, $F : \Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$, and $n_0, n_1 : \mathbb N$ with $n_0 + 1 = n_1$. Then the iter-022 sequence
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence}\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h
  \]
  is exact (in the sense of $\mathtt{ComposableArrows.Exact}$).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequenceIso}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L140--141). Body: \lstinline{ComposableArrows.exact_of_iso (HModule'_sequenceIso k S F n₀ n₁ h).symm (Ext.contravariantSequence_exact _ _ _ _ _)}. The reasoning is: the iter-023 iso $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequenceIso}$ shows the iter-022 sequence is isomorphic to Mathlib's $\Ext.\mathtt{contravariantSequence}$, which is exact by Mathlib's $\Ext.\mathtt{contravariantSequence\_exact}$; exactness transports across iso via $\mathtt{ComposableArrows.exact\_of\_iso}$. Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-026) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end against the post-iter-025 file with $\{success : true, diagnostics : []\}$, kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[$\delta\,\circ\,\toBiprod = 0$ (iter-026)]
  \label{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta_toBiprod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_δ_toBiprod}
  \uses{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}
  Under the same hypotheses,
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\delta\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h \;\circ\; \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n_1 \;=\; 0.
  \]
  Carries the attribute $\mathtt{@[reassoc\ (attr := simp)]}$ (matches Mathlib L143).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{\delta\_toBiprod}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L143--145). One-liner consequence of Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}: the LES exactness implies that any two consecutive arrows compose to zero, in particular the ($\delta$, $\toBiprod$ at $n_1$) pair at sequence-position $2$. Body: \lstinline{(HModule'_sequence_exact k S F n₀ n₁ h).zero 2}. Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-026) confirms.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[$\fromBiprod\,\circ\,\delta = 0$ (iter-026)]
  \label{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod_delta}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_fromBiprod_δ}
  \uses{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}
  Under the same hypotheses,
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n_0 \;\circ\; \HModulePrime\_\delta\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h \;=\; 0.
  \]
  Carries the attribute $\mathtt{@[reassoc\ (attr := simp)]}$ (matches Mathlib L147).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{fromBiprod\_\delta}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L147--149). One-liner consequence of Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence_exact}: the same exactness argument applied at sequence-position $1$ (the ($\fromBiprod$ at $n_0$, $\delta$) pair). Body: \lstinline{(HModule'_sequence_exact k S F n₀ n₁ h).zero 1}. Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-026) confirms.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Mayer-Vietoris LES build-out: status after iter-026]
  Iter-026 closes the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavored Mayer-Vietoris LES build-out (Mathlib \texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L43--149 mirror). The closed cohort comprises:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item iter-014: carrier $\HModulePrime$.
    \item iter-015: $H^0$ algebraic bridge $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{zero\_linearEquiv}$.
    \item iter-016: functorial wrappers $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheafFunctor$ + $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf$.
    \item iter-017: LES building blocks $\HModulePrime\_\toBiprod$ + $\HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod$.
    \item iter-018: composition-is-zero relation $\HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\_\fromBiprod$.
    \item iter-019: short-complex carrier $\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex$ + $\mathtt{isPushoutModuleCatFreeSheaf}$ + $(\ModuleCat.\free\,k).\IsLeftAdjoint$ Mathlib gap-fill.
    \item iter-020: $\Mono$ / $\Epi$ / $\Exact$ / $\ShortExact$ infrastructure on the short complex + $(\ModuleCat.\free\,k).\PreservesMonomorphisms$ Mathlib gap-fill.
    \item iter-021: connecting hom $\HModulePrime\_\delta$.
    \item iter-022: LES sequence $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence}$.
    \item iter-023: four auxiliary lemmas + comparison iso $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequenceIso}$ (the technical heart).
    \item iter-026: exactness theorem $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ + $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions $\HModulePrime\_\delta\_\toBiprod$ + $\HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\_\delta$ (this section).
  \end{itemize}

  Iter-027 starts a fresh cycle: split this file along the natural semantic boundary (the iter-016--iter-026 MV-LES infrastructure moves to a new file $\mathtt{Cohomology/MayerVietoris.lean}$), then iter-028+ begins the Serre-finiteness work specialised to a $2$-affine cover of a proper $k$-curve --- the multi-iteration theorem $\Module.\Finite\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,i)$ for $F = \toModuleKSheaf\,C$, which $\mathtt{smoothOfRelativeDimension\_genus}$ (one of the four \texttt{Jacobian.lean} instances) will eventually consume.

  Iter-026 sorry-count trajectory: $9 \to 12 \to 9$ (three new \lstinline{sorry} sites in the three lemmas; all filled in the iter-026 prover round).
\end{remark}

